Citizenship? / rCheckel, Jeffirey T. -- t11. A European Identity? Europeanization and the Evolution of Nation-State Identities / rRisse, Thomas -- t12. Transforming Europe: Conclusions / rCowles, Maria Green / Risse, Thomas -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex  aDoes the European Union change the domestic politics and institutions of its member states? Many studies of EU decisionmaking in Brussels pay little attention to the potential domestic impact of European integration. Transforming Europe traces the effects of Europeanization on the EU member states. The various chapters, based on cutting-edge research, examine the impact of the EU on national court systems, territorial politics, societal networks, public discourse, identity, and citizenship norms.The European Union, the authors find, does indeed make a difference-even in Germany, France, and the United Kingdom. In many cases EU rules and regulations incompatible with domestic institutions have created pressure for national governments to adapt. This volume examines the conditions under which this "adaptational pressure" has led to institutional change in the member states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2019) 0aNationalismzEuropean Union countries. 0aPolicy scienceszEuropean Union countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aCaporaso, James, eeditor.1 aCowles, Maria Green, eeditor.1 aRisse, Thomas, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501723575423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501723575.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA1